Colin,



If I understand your approach correctly, this sounds interesting.  I wish to
clarify your use of some terms derived from the term &quot;space&quot;, and
specifically &quot;behavioural space&quot; and &quot;geographical space&quot;.  Is the first a
morphism or perhaps a mapping onto or between spaces? Is the second
descriptive of shapes between degrees of freedom and regions?  For example,
are these terms generally referring to topological or manifold spaces?
Coming from a foundation of category theory, I&#39;ve found it dangerous for me
to assume what one means by &quot;geographical space&quot;, because it might be
limited to a particular Cartesian physical world-space.



I would agree that topological and other meaningful, spatial domains *are*
missing from NEAT-based search spaces, and that these might affect the
directions of evolution.



Also, I think the notion of substitutability with various, alternate
&quot;modules&quot;, categories of classes, is an excellent developmental approach.
Even these can be evolved.



==========================

Kenneth A. Lloyd, Jr.

CEO - Director, Systems Science

Watt Systems Technologies Inc.

Albuquerque, NM USA







